metadata.name: CA Panico #164
metadata.description:
Third chapter of the trilogy dedicated to Stephen Wolfram's cellular automata.
 
Compared to CA Vista and CA Monti, CA Panico aims to further abstract the concept of landscape using CA rules in a more massive way.

The great variety of CA rules that controls the coloring and textures, noise influence, division into quadrants, chance of having glitches and outages all combined with 25 palettes and 5 different formats means that the outputs will be very varied and peculiar.

Press 'S' to download, you can zoom downloaded output to enjoy all the details.

metadata.name: an unrelated entity #86
metadata.description:
An experiment in maximal minimalism. The human brain's ability to deduce patterns and imagery given the the most basic input has always amazed me. Three circles and a handful of straight lines become a blazing sun and tall trees on a plain. 

I say "maximal" because this is far more code than I normally use; the "paper" alone is more code than my last three mints combined. The icons in the lower left are as follows: 

First icon: a binary representation of the transaction hash. 
Second icon: a meter denoting number of "trees"
Remaining icons: denote the boolean traits - sun, ring, and leaves.

Created in p5.js

metadata.name: Tangentum #29
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: impressions 01 #48
metadata.description:
Patterns in patterns, created in code. Each one unique, but all part of a family. 

Traits:

Shape - The starting shape, either ellipse or square. 
XRand & YRand - The amount of rescaling randomization. 
Divisions - The X/Y resolution of the pattern. 

Created in p5.js

metadata.name: Kleurstalen #106
metadata.description: "Kleurstalen" is a simple experiment that uses fxhash's iteration property to pick colors just once. In total there are 140 editions, representing the commonly used named colors in modern web browsers. Each edition corresponds to a single color from the set, allowing collectors to - in some way - own a color! Now, the question remains: who will get the color "hotpink"?

metadata.name: FSM #69
metadata.description:
FSM is a visual grid-system based on autopoiesis, the principle of self-organization through self-reproduction central to cybernetics. At the heart of FSM is a computational mechanism, a finite-state machine (FSM), which generates sequences of visual outputs by activating particular agents and cycling them through varying sets of configurations.

The grid-system in FSM is segmented along three axes: horizontal, vertical, and diagonal. This segmentation constitutes the machine’s parametric space.

Certain agents and configurations are programmed to appear exclusively in specific grid segments, illustrating a principle of spatial distribution.

Similarly, spatial distribution is mirrored by temporal distribution. Specific agents and configurations are set to emerge at predetermined time intervals. This interplay turns FSM in a self-organizing system living on the blockchain.

The underlying grid of the animation is responsive. Try to change your window size to get different aspect ratios and grid configurations. On the project page you'll find a tool to adjust some parameters via queries components.
Please visit: http://fsm.julian-h.de for more information

CONTROLS
[f] To enter fullscreen mode
[spacebar] Play or pause the animation
[s] Export current frame as a PNG
[g] Capture a small GIF
[G] Press once to start capturing a GIF and press [G] again to stop the capture process.

Created using p5.js and GLSL.

Julian Hespenheide, 2023

metadata.name: Cold Mountain #152
metadata.description:
An impressionistic painting of a maintain on a foggy winter's day. The view will be of a mountain, mountain range, valley, or meadow. At nite, the lights come on, and the trees glow in the moonlight.

The image size is 928x1200. Press 's' to save a screenshot.

Common features:
- mountain size and stroke quality
- line quality of the trees
- 50/50 to have a spiral around the sun
- large palette with different application methods

Uncommon
- outline of the first mountain and sun
- amplified color/hue shifting

Rare
- nighttime
- no sun
